significantly, from growing things to selling them exemplified the enormous social effort required to domesticate the profit motive and turn it into the practical foundation of civic life. As Zakim reveals in his highly original study, there was nothing natural or preordained about the stunning ascendance of this capitalism and its radical transformation of the relationship between "Man and Mammon."   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2020) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aClerkszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aaccounting. 4acapitalism. 4aindividualism. 4aknowledge. 4amarket economy. 4amasculinity. 4anervous disorders. 4aoffice work. 4apaperwork. 4astatistics. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP Multi-User eBook-Package 2018z978311070866040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226545899423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226545899.jpg  a978-3-11-070866-0  UChP Multi-User eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles